The Telegraph - Calcutta : International
 Saturday, July 03, 2004 				 Mayor shot dead by Maoists
																								Kathmandu, July 2 (PTI): The mayor of Pokhara, a Nepali tourist town, was today assassinated by suspected Maoist militants who had earlier warned him to resign.																								The shooting took place in a busy marketplace in Pokhara, 200 km west of Kathmandu. Three Maoist militants were involved in the shooting of the mayor Harkha Bahadur Gurung, home ministry sources said. The Maoists fired five rounds at Gurung, who was going to his office, killing him on the spot.																								The mayors bodyguard and driver were also seriously injured in the incident. They were airlifted to Kathmandu and admitted to a hospital for treatment. The Maoists had earlier asked Gurung to resign and issued death threats if he did not step down. A search has been launched to hunt those who were involved in the shootout.																								In separate incidents, ten Maoist rebels have been killed in the latest security operations across the country, the government-run Gorkhapatra daily said quoting defence ministry sources. A soldier was also killed during the clashes, the ministry said. 
